ayers. I'm also considering the `bootstrap.memory_lock` setting for the Kubernetes cluster.\n\nFor the initial master nodes configuration, I need to reference the actual pod names like `es-cluster-0`, `es-cluster-1`, and `es-cluster-2`. Now I'm setting up the TLS certificate generation process, starting with creating a CA certificate and then configuring OpenSSL with Subject Alternative Names for the cluster nodes.\n\nWriting certificate generation script... Generating certificate signing request and certificate... Writing OpenSSL command...\n\nI should keep the existing services since they're already configured correctly for the cluster. The main thing I need to update is the ConfigMap for Elasticsearch 8.x compatibility, and then modify the StatefulSet accordingly.\n\nFor the upgrade itself, I'll need to handle the incompatible 7.x data by deleting the PVCs, then update the StatefulSet with the new image, mount the TLS certificate from a secret, add the elastic password environment variable, and adjust the readiness probe to work with HTTPS. Since I'm making multiple changes to the StatefulSet including volumes and environment variables, I'll delete and recreate it rather than patch. The PVCs need explicit deletion since they won't be removed automatically due to retention policies.\n\nMy execution plan covers generating the TLS certificates, creating the necessary secrets, updating the ConfigMap with ES 8.11.1 settings, deleting the old StatefulSet and PVCs, deploying the new StatefulSet, waiting for readiness, and verifying connectivity.\n\nWriting Elasticsearch config... Now I'm setting up the StatefulSet with the Elasticsearch 8.11.1 image, configuring environment variables for the pod name and Java heap settings, mounting the config file and TLS certificates, and defining a readiness probe that uses curl to check HTTPS connectivity with authentication.\n\nI need to verify that bash is available in the Elasticsearch container—it's Ubuntu-based so it should be fine. Before I write out the complete YAML manifest, I realize I need to create the TLS secret `es-http-tls` first since it doesn't exist in the cluster yet.\n\nGenerating TLS certificates and creating secrets... Writing certificate and secret creation commands... Configuring SSL certificates for both HTTP and transport layer security...\n\nNow I'm deleting the existing StatefulSet with foreground cascade to ensure pods terminate cleanly, then removing the persistent volume claims since they're retained by default. I need to be careful about resource allocation—ES 8.11.1 with a 512MB JVM heap requires specific configuration considerations.\n\nFor the readiness probe, I'm setting up HTTPS authentication that retrieves the password from an environment variable and checks the cluster health endpoint.\n\nFor liveness, a TCP socket probe on the transport port is simpler and more reliable than HTTP checks. I should also account for the startup time of Elasticsearch 8.11.1 with security and TLS enabled, so I'll need to configure appropriate initial delay settings. Writing probe configuration... Finishing the StatefulSet configuration... I'm realizing I need to handle the permissions issue for the Elasticsearch data directory in the kind cluster. Since the PVC is typically owned by root but Elasticsearch runs as the `elasticsearch` user, I should use `fsGroup: 1000` in the pod's security context to let Kubernetes automatically chown the volumes to the right group. I'm considering using an init container with busybox to fix permissions on the data volume, but that requires root access. The simpler approach is just setting `fsGroup: 1000` at the pod level, which Kubernetes will use to automatically set the GID of mounted volumes—this should work fine with kind clusters and is the recommended way to handle this.\n\nNow I need to set the initial password for Elasticsearch using the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable, which the official image's entrypoint script will pick up during first bootstrap. I'll go with something like `changeme123` for simplicity. I also need to make sure the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` setting matches the StatefulSet pod names exactly—so for a three-node cluster that would be `es-cluster-0`, `es-cluster-1`, and `es-cluster-2`.\n\nFor ES 8.11.1, the transport layer uses TLS 1.2 or 1.3, and with `verification_mode: certificate` it will verify the certificate is signed by the CA without doing hostname verification, which should work fine for this setup. I'm also considering whether to disable `xpack.security.enrollment.enabled` since we're using the traditional seed hosts and initial master nodes approach for bootstrapping the cluster, though I need to verify if that's actually necessary. I'll use the fully qualified domain names for the seed hosts to ensure reliable discovery across the cluster. Now I'm thinking through the kubectl commands to execute this setup, considering whether to use foreground or background cascade deletion for the StatefulSet—background cascade will be faster, so I'll delete the StatefulSet and then wait for the pods to terminate separately.\n\nFor the readiness probe, I'm reconsidering between a TCP socket check and an HTTP probe with basic auth. Since Elasticsearch 8.x has security enabled by default, I want to verify the cluster is actually serving HTTPS and functional, but basic auth requires base64 encoding in the HTTP header which adds complexity.\n\nI'm going to use an exec probe with curl instead—it's cleaner and lets me check the cluster health endpoint directly with the password passed as an environment variable, avoiding hardcoded credentials in the probe definition. I need to make sure the `node.store.allow_mmap: false` setting stays in place for Docker compatibility, and `network.host: 0.0.0.0` lets the container listen across all interfaces. The inter-node communication will work fine through the discovery seed hosts without needing to configure the publish host separately. Now I'm ready to write out the full solution, though I should double-check how ES 8.x handles the password environment variable in the container entrypoint. The existing services are fine as-is—both the headless `es-cluster` service on port 9300 and the `es-http` service on port 9200 work correctly with ES 8.x, even with TLS enabled since HTTPS uses the same port. Now I'll write out the actual commands to fix this.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2950,"cache_read_input_tokens":34161,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2950},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6d0a60f6-1590-4ef0-bc65-15cfc3fb7e9c","uuid":"a6aedab7-c020-4840-bc14-974970499063","request_id":"req_011CcQ9davAmJkyPKKYRVXmB"}
